**Steps to Reproduce**:

Open the lightbulb menu somewhere in the variable declaration and select one of the "Encapsulate fields" refactorings.

```csharp
internal static class C
{
    internal const string
        A = nameof(A),
        B = nameof(B);
}
```

**Expected Behavior**: All rewritten fields retain their existing values.

**Actual Behavior**:
All constants, apart from the one on which the refactoring was started, lose their value, leading to error CS0145.
```csharp
internal static class C
{
    private const string // <-- side note: weird line break here - probably carried over from original source?
        b = nameof(B);
    private const string a; // <-- CS0145: A const field requires a value to be provided

    internal static string A => a;

    internal static string B => b;
}
```

I'm using .NET SDK **10.0.102**. I've noticed a difference in nullability checks when using the classic extension method syntax rather than the new extension keyword, as you can see in the following example:

```csharp
using System;
using System.IO;

// No warnings
Console.Out.WriteLines_Old("Hello", "World!");

// CS8620: Argument of type 'string' cannot be used for parameter 'values' of type 'string[]' in
// 'void extension(TextWriter).WriteLines_New(params string[] values)' due to differences in the nullability of reference types.
Console.Out.WriteLines_New("Hello", "World!");

public static class ConsoleExtensions
{
    public static void WriteLines_Old(this TextWriter writer, params string[] values)
    {
        foreach (var value in values)
        {
            writer.WriteLine(value);
        }
    }

    extension(TextWriter writer)
    {
        public void WriteLines_New(params string[] values)
        {
            foreach (var value in values)
            {
                writer.WriteLine(value);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

**CS8620**

`Argument of type 'string' cannot be used for parameter 'values' of type 'string[]' in 'void extension(TextWriter).WriteLines_New(params string[] values)' due to differences in the nullability of reference types.`

